[1] Germany (Cologne, North Rhine-Westphalia)
Date: Mon 28 May 2018
Source: Wunderweib [in German, machine trans., edited]
https://www.wunderweib.de/masern-faelle-in-koeln-groesster-ausbruch-der-krankheit-seit-16-jahren-103555.html


In Cologne [Cologne, North Rhine-Westphalia], 68 people are suffering from measles [the largest outbreak since] 16 years ago. The highly contagious disease affects all age groups.

In 2001 there were 500 measles cases in Cologne. Thereafter, the number ebbed away; in 2002, according to the Robert Koch Institute, 78 people were affected by the infectious disease. In between, the numbers were about 43 cases. 2018 is not even halfway over and the city is already reporting 68 measles patients. "One can speak of a worrying situation," said professor Gerhard Wiesm√ºller of the infection and environmental hygiene of the Cologne health department to RP-Online. "There is no group that is particularly affected."

The districts of Ehrenfeld and Neuehrenfeld are especially affected, according to the health authorities. But in other cities in North Rhine-Westphalia -- apart from Cologne -- there are measles cases:
Duisburg: 34 cases
Dusseldorf: 1 case
Hagen: 4 cases
Rhein-Erft-Kreis: 6 cases

In North Rhine-Westphalia, 126 people suffer from measles. However, there are also cases throughout Europe in Bulgaria, Romania, Greece, France, and the Czech Republic.

